<DOC><DOCNO> AP891220-0053 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-89 0518EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i BC-Panama-SovietReax 1stLd-Writethru a0511 12-20 0197</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Panama-Soviet Reax, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0511,0197</SECOND><HEAD>Soviets Condemn U.S. Attack on Noriega</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Radio Moscow condemning the attack,later Tass report identifying the Foreign Ministry official. No pickup.</HEAD><DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Soviet Union on Wednesday swiftly condemnedthe U.S. armed intervention in Panama and demanded it endimmediately.   ``The United States has launched an act of aggression againstPanama,'' state-run Radio Moscow reported. It said the CentralAmerican country was the victim of an American military``invasion.''   ``These actions, a violation of the U.N. Charter and generallyrecognized rules of state relations, should be condemned by theinternational community,'' Foreign Ministry spokesman Vadim P.Perfiliev said. ``The United States must immediately stop its armedintervention in Panama.''   Perfiliev was quoted by the official Tass news agency as sayingthat the U.S. action, ``whatever its motivation, has provoked afeeling of serious concern in the Soviet Union.''   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said President Bushordered U.S. troops to seize the Panamanian leader, Gen. ManuelAntonio Noriega, and bring him to the United States for trial onfederal drug charges.   Tass said Perfiliev commented in response to questions fromreporters.</TEXT></DOC>